      "type": "reference",
      "id": "339bdf3913f48ed5",
      "site": "wiki.ralfbarkow.ch",
      "slug": "embodied-cognition",
      "title": "Embodied Cognition",
      "text": "Traditional views in philosophy of mind and cognitive science depict the mind as an information processor, one whose connections with the body and the world are of little theoretical importance."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "db777f62f5c7b478",
      "text": "An illustration of this idea comes from the joint work of George Lakoff and Mark Johnson. Beginning in their [[Metaphors We Live By]], Lakoff and Johnson argued that many central cognitive processes, such as those concerning space and time, are both expressed and influenced by metaphors, and that many metaphors reflect bodily features. "
    },
