      "id": "db777f62f5c7b478",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "db777f62f5c7b478",
        "text": "An illustration of this idea comes from the joint work of George Lakoff and Mark Johnson. Beginning in their [[Metaphors We Live By]], Lakoff and Johnson argued that many central cognitive processes, such as those concerning space and time, are both expressed and influenced by metaphors, and that many metaphors reflect bodily features. Consider a well-known metaphor that they discuss: that of love as a kind of journey. Here the source domain (journey) is informed by our bodily physicality, and information about the body (such as its capacity for locomotion) shapes the way in which love is understood and conceptualized. Metaphors, hence, are not merely useful for embellishing communication, but reflect the embodied experience that we have as creatures that move through the world in particular ways."
      },
      "date": 1675289784621
